<i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Parker was born in 1204 as the son of Miles Le Parker. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1264, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1204–1264":"1204–1264","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1180–1264":"1180–1264","1204":"1204","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1204–1264":"1204–1264","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1180–1264":"1180–1264","1204":"1204","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1204–1264":"1204–1264","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1180–1264":"1180–1264","1204":"1204","1264":"1264","1230":"1230","1180":"1180","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William Parker est né en 1204, fils de Miles Le Parker. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1